description:
dan added on 2018-12-20 17:30:57:
In 3.26.0 and earlier, a foreign key may malfunction if the parent and child are the same WITHOUT ROWID table, and the parent key is not the same as the primary key.
The problem can occur either when deleting (no constraint failure when there should be one) or inserting (deferred constraint failure when there should not be one) a row.
In 3.26.0 and earlier, the last SQL statement in the following fails to report the constraint error.
PRAGMA foreign_keys=ON;
  CREATE TABLE t2(
    a PRIMARY KEY, b, c, d, e,
    FOREIGN KEY(b, c) REFERENCES t2(d, e)
  ) WITHOUT ROWID;
  CREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx ON t2(d, e);

  INSERT INTO t2 VALUES(1, 'one', 'one', 'one', 'one'); -- row is parent of self
  INSERT INTO t2 VALUES(2, 'one', 'one', 'one', NULL);  -- parent is row 1

  DELETE FROM t2 WHERE a=1;
